<note><term xml:lang="ta">koṇṭamaiyiṉ</term>: Cām. reads an abstract noun in -<term xml:lang="ta">mai</term> from the perfective peyareccam + -<term xml:lang="ta">iṉ</term> oblique. Would it not be better to read <term xml:lang="ta">koṇṭu amaiyiṉ</term>, the usual abs. to <term xml:lang="ta">koḷ</term> + cond. to <term xml:lang="ta">amai</term>, 4th class, "to become quite"? It is true that there are parallels for such a mode of expression, like in KT 173.7 <term xml:lang="ta">uṇarntamaiyiṉ</term>. On the other hand there are passages like KT 132.3 with <term xml:lang="ta">maṟantu amaiku</term> (see also KT 137.2, 225.5; cf. also KT 117.5 abs.neg. + <term xml:lang="ta">amaiyiṉ</term>), i.e. unequivocally absolutive + amai, so that the question is justified whether <term xml:lang="ta">amai</term> can be understood as an auxiliary verb.</note>
